{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Indi is many things. We all are, of course, but ve is a wonderful example when it comes to building up the critter you want to be out of the things that are important to you. Ve is most commonly a plush coyotter \u8212- a coyote/otter hybrid in stuffed animal form \u8212- covered in glowy markings in teal, purple, and green. Everything is chosen very deliberately. Ver constituent species is each important to ver in its own way, as well as each of the colors chosen as\u8230?tattoos? Markings? Shifting signifiers of emotion, attitude, and status.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 You see, this is why I love postfurries so much. No other crowd that I\u8217've had the chance to spend time with has been so interested in self-actualization of so many portions of their identity. Postfurry is a topic for another piece, but it\u8217's worth bringing up that Indi typifies the class: ve is doing ver best to find a way to not just emulate but become what ve feels verself to be, but to actually achieve that as ver reality.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This naturally finds its way into the ways in which ve experiences, expresses, and talks about gender. You\u8217've noticed the pronoun choices, surely \u8212- ve/ver/vis \u8212- but it\u8217's worth talking a little about how exactly Indi identifies, as well as how ve got there and how furry helped.\par}
